content.description: Starts very low, STD, with left hand on small nub and right hand in a sloper under-cling. Move up nice pockets and compression side pulls to the lip of the prow. Top out.
content.location: Top out should get better as time goes on.  Tread carefully or opt out of a true ascent and walk off left.

content.description: Start as low as possible on jugs with a gaston/undercling combo.  Make a couple moves up to nice jugs and pull the bulge to a slab.  Crux is first few moves and pulling the bulge. Just a few moves and this one is done. Walk off to the left

Start low nice rails or standing and move to crimp side pull and two finger pocket, move up through a disguising sea of moss to find decent pockets all the way up to a series of knobs and rails for top out.
content.protection: A few Pads and a spotter
content.location: This is one of those typical joinerville honeycomb looking climbs with thin limestone and small nuggets that tend to break off.  Be cautious which holds you grab and where you place your feet.  Hopefully with time and more traffic there will be less moss and better rock.

content.description: Sit down start as low as possible on questionable looking rock.  Move into the obvious crack and traverse up the arête towards the prow. Top out all the way to the top through the jungle of crap or opt out and walk off left on the slab.
content.location: It does Top out but rock is questionable so tread carefully.  Feel Free to Help clean on your way up!

content.description: Sit down start far right , move to jugs and climb up to nice top out rail.  Easy Climbing.

Starts Left hand in an amazing side pull, right hand on a sloped face. Move right to a nice pocket with a sharp lip and work your way straight up just left of the prow .  Crux is reaching over the bulge to good holds. May be easier for taller climbers!  Not sure if it is 4 star worthy but it is really fun once you figure out the beta.

A good mix of fun over hung low ball climbing on one side , a nice arête in the middle, and a high ball wall on the other side.  There has always been chalk here and there on this wall but top outs were prevented by a couple big fallen trees hanging over and a very thick layer of moss + 4" top soil making top out holds non existent.  Work has recently been done to remove fallen trees, scrub moss , and remove soil but there is still quite a bit of cleaning and scrubbing to be done before this becomes quality climbing.
